│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.  │
│ **Understanding the Issue**: The crash is an assertion       │
│ failure `Dereferencing deleted ValueHandle` inside           │
│ `llvm::peelLoop`. This assertion indicates that we are       │
│ trying to access a `Value` that has already been deleted     │
│ from the IR, through a `WeakTrackingVH`. The                 │
│ `WeakTrackingVH` correctly identifies this situation and     │
│ aborts the program to prevent further corruption.\n\n2.      │
│ **Analyzing `opt`'s Log**: The `opt` debug log shows that    │
│ the `loop-unroll` pass decides to peel one iteration from    │
│ the loop `%loop`.\n    ```\n    Loop Unroll:                 │
│ F[pr142895_exit_value_is_inst] Loop %loop\n      Loop Size = │
│ 7\n    Peel 0 iteration(s) to turn some Phis into            │
│ invariants.\n    PEELING loop %loop with iteration count     │
│ 1!\n    ```\n    The backtrace confirms the crash occurs     │
│ within the `llvm::peelLoop` function, which is called by     │
│ `tryToUnrollLoop`.\n\n3. **Root Cause Analysis**:\n    The   │
│ crash happens at                                             │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/LoopPeel.cpp:1260`:\n    ```cpp\n │
│ // 1257: Now adjust users of the original exit values by     │
│ replacing them with the\n    // 1258: exit value from the    │
│ peeled iteration and remove them.\n    // 1259: for (const   │
│ auto &[P, E] : ExitValues) {\n    // 1260:                   │
│ P->replaceAllUsesWith(isa<Constant>(E) ? E :                 │
│ &*VMap.lookup(E));\n    // 1261:   P->eraseFromParent();\n   │
│ // 1262: }\n    ```\n    Here, `P` is an LCSSA PHI node in a │
│ loop exit block, and `E` is the incoming value from the      │
│ loop. In our reproducer, `P` is `%exit.lcssa` and `E` is     │
│ `%mul`. The code intends to replace the LCSSA PHI with the   │
│ corresponding value from the peeled iteration.\n\n    The    │
│ expression `&*VMap.lookup(E)` triggers the assertion. `VMap` │
│ maps original values from the loop to their cloned           │
│ counterparts in the peeled iteration. `VMap.lookup(E)`       │
│ returns a `WeakTrackingVH`. The `*` operator dereferences    │
│ this handle, and the assertion fires because the `Value` it  │
│ was tracking has been deleted (or in this case, was never    │
│ there, so the handle is null).\n\n    The value `E` (`%mul`) │
│ is defined outside the loop, in the preheader. When peeling, │
│ `remapInstructionsInBlocks` is used to create the peeled     │
│ iteration. This function remaps operands. If an operand is   │
│ defined outside the loop, it's generally not remapped and    │
│ the original value is used. Crucially, `%mul` is not part of │
│ the blocks being cloned and therefore is not added to        │
│ `VMap`.\n\n    The logic at line 1260 incorrectly assumes    │
│ that if `E` is not a constant, it must have been part of the │
│ cloned loop body and therefore present in `VMap`. Since      │
│ `%mul` is not in `VMap`, `VMap.lookup(E)` returns a          │
│ default-constructed `WeakTrackingVH` which points to         │
│ `nullptr`. Dereferencing this triggers the assertion.\n\n    │
