│ replacing them with the                                      │
│     // 1258: exit value from the peeled iteration and remove │
│ them.                                                        │
│     // 1259: for (const auto &[P, E] : ExitValues) {         │
│     // 1260:   P->replaceAllUsesWith(isa<Constant>(E) ? E :  │
│ &*VMap.lookup(E));                                           │
│     // 1261:   P->eraseFromParent();                         │
│     // 1262: }                                               │
│     ```                                                      │
│     Here, `P` is an LCSSA PHI node in a loop exit block, and │
│ `E` is the incoming value from the loop. In our reproducer,  │
│ `P` is `%exit.lcssa` and `E` is `%mul`. The code intends to  │
│ replace the LCSSA PHI with the corresponding value from the  │
│ peeled iteration.                                            │
│                                                              │
│     The expression `&*VMap.lookup(E)` triggers the           │
│ assertion. `VMap` maps original values from the loop to      │
│ their cloned counterparts in the peeled iteration.           │
│ `VMap.lookup(E)` returns a `WeakTrackingVH`. The `*`         │
│ operator dereferences this handle, and the assertion fires   │
│ because the `Value` it was tracking has been deleted (or in  │
│ this case, was never there, so the handle is null).          │
│                                                              │
│     The value `E` (`%mul`) is defined outside the loop, in   │
│ the preheader. When peeling, `remapInstructionsInBlocks` is  │
│ used to create the peeled iteration. This function remaps    │
│ operands. If an operand is defined outside the loop, it's    │
│ generally not remapped and the original value is used.       │
│ Crucially, `%mul` is not part of the blocks being cloned and │
│ therefore is not added to `VMap`.                            │
